The paper proposes a new game-theoretic model for network formation, which falls under the category of algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The model focuses on social effort and the emergence of complex social structures, which aligns with the sub-categories of social and information networks (cs.SOC, cs.SI). The paper also analyzes the Nash equilibria of the game, which involves constructing social networks with given degree sequences, indicating a connection to the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the benefits and costs of organizing networking events, which relates to the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT).
